The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Bindra wants to be adventurous
                                                   Bindra wants to be adventurous
            A STAFF REPORTER                      
	Calcutta: Indias lone individual Olympic gold medallist, Abhinav Bindra, wants to be a little more adventurous and said he was contemplating competing in another event.         
	I have no plans of changing my event, but I may try a little adventure and compete in another event, he said without specifying what his next competition would be.         
	Addressing about a dozen young shooters from the state, the world champion in the 10m Air Rifle event, said: Keep focussing on the process that will take you to that performance level Focus on the technique.         
	Bindra, who also gave away copies of his book, Ways of the Rifle 2009, to each youngster, felicitated his psychological trainer Amit Bhattacharya. Bhattacharya, who hails from the Nadia district, has been with Bindra for the last 13 years.         
	The Olympic gold medallist also hailed the citys sports culture and said he had enjoyed every bit of his two-day visit.         
	I think Calcutta can boast of a great sporting culture. The rest of the country needs to draw inspiration from here. The people here enjoy sports, Bindra said. The ace shooter wants to be a little more adventurous and was contemplating competing in another event.         
	On the significance of his gold medal, Bindra said: Its a dream I dreamt for 15 years. Its a jinx we as a country broke. Now we can dream of more gold.                                                                                                                       
